{
  "query": "What are the documented effects of removing competing understory vegetation on planted trees and overall forest biodiversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies, removing competing understory vegetation after planting showed mixed effects on planted trees and variable outcomes for biodiversity. Mechanical removal after planting had no effect on emergence, survival, growth rate, or frost damage in most studies, though one study reported increased seedling biomass, and another found that removing sheep laurel shrubs increased the growth rate and height of planted black spruce seedlings [1256]. Using herbicides after planting increased the size of planted trees in two of three studies, while one study found no effect on size; a replicated study found no effect on frost damage to Norway spruce seedlings [1262]. When vegetation removal was combined with mechanical soil disturbance, studies reported increased cover and diversity of understory plants, decreased understory shrub cover, and increased density of young trees [1274].",
  "action_ids": [
    "1256",
    "1262",
    "1274"
  ]
}

